Subject: [PATCH] Use target_compile_options for include dirs (conda-forge/cmake#106)

CMake intentionally strips paths in CMAKE_<LANG>_IMPLICIT_INCLUDE_DIRECTORIES
from -I/-isystem flags generated by target_include_directories, to avoid
interfering with #include_next on stdlib headers.

In conda-forge cross-compiler environments, gcc's specs don't bake in
$PREFIX/include; the path is only ever passed via CPPFLAGS/CXXFLAGS in
the activation script. CMake's configure-time probe mis-classifies
$PREFIX/include as implicit (via activated CXXFLAGS) and strips it from
target_include_directories outputs. Combined with the OBJECT-library
code path here not propagating CMAKE_<LANG>_FLAGS into flags.make's
CXX_FLAGS, headers under $PREFIX/include become unfindable.

Switching to raw -I via target_compile_options bypasses the stripping
(documented conda-forge workaround) and reaches every compile reliably.
Relative entries in ${DIRECTORIES} are absolutised first since
target_compile_options doesn't rebase paths like target_include_directories
does.

See: https://github.com/conda-forge/cmake-feedstock/issues/106

--- a/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -282,7 +282,15 @@
 # compile the Uno source files once, whatever the compilation type is (static or shared)
 add_library(compiled_uno_files OBJECT ${UNO_SOURCE_FILES})
 set_property(TARGET compiled_uno_files PROPERTY POSITION_INDEPENDENT_CODE ON)
-target_include_directories(compiled_uno_files SYSTEM PUBLIC ${DIRECTORIES})
+# Use target_compile_options with raw -I flags instead of
+# target_include_directories(... SYSTEM ...) so the paths bypass CMake's
+# implicit-include-directory stripping (see conda-forge/cmake-feedstock#106).
+foreach(_uno_dir IN LISTS DIRECTORIES)
+   if(NOT IS_ABSOLUTE "${_uno_dir}")
+      set(_uno_dir "${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/${_uno_dir}")
+   endif()
+   target_compile_options(compiled_uno_files PUBLIC "-I${_uno_dir}")
+endforeach()
 target_link_libraries(compiled_uno_files PUBLIC ${LIBRARIES} ${FORTRAN_LIBS})
 
 if(BUILD_STATIC_LIBS)
